President Donald J. Trump announced his intent to nominate Mary Beth Leonard of Massachusetts as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Nigeria. Leonard is currently serving as the U.S. Ambassador to the African Union and has previously held various positions in the U.S. Department of State. She has a B.A. from Boston University, an M.A. from Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies, and an M.A. from the U.S. Naval War College.

President Trump also announced his intent to nominate Herro Mustafa of California as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Bulgaria. Mustafa is currently the Deputy Chief of Mission of the U.S. Embassy in Lisbon, Portugal, and has held several positions in the U.S. Department of State and the White House. She has a B.S.F.S degree from Georgetown University and an M.P.A. from Princeton University.

Additionally, President Trump announced his intent to appoint Chad Rupe of Wyoming as the Administrator of the Rural Utilities Service, U.S. Department of Agriculture. Rupe has been serving as the Acting Administrator since April 2019 and previously served as the USDA Rural Development State Director of Wyoming. He has experience in rural broadband and water utilities projects and has a background in commercial lending and military service. Rupe is a graduate of the United States Military Academy at West Point and earned his MBA from the University of Phoenix.